<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-706-806  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 706 806.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 25 1989 v6 n38 p40(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Competitive CAD for less: American Small Business Computers Inc.,andO;DesignCAD 3.1, $299. (Software Review) (CAD Programs on a LAN; oneof three CAD program evaluations) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis-Wright, Ryan; Moser, Karen.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>American Small Business Computers Inc's $299 DesignCAD 3.1requires only 512Kbytes of memory, making it a good program for640Kbyte computers with network drivers loaded.andP;  DesignCAD cannotuse over 768Kbytes of expanded memory, however, which can causeproblems when using files of approximately 1Mbyte.andP;  The programimported the DXF files into its format without problems, but itenlarged the largest file from 457Kbytes to 509Kbytes.andP;  DesignCADcompared favorably with AutoCAD and VersaCAD-386 in the tests, buttook the longest to save the largest files on both networks.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Small Business Computers Inc. (products).andO;Product:   DesignCAD 3.1 (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     EvaluationLocal Area NetworksGraphics SoftwareComputer-aided designMemory.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Competitive CAD for LessandM;AMERICAN SMALL BUSINESS COMPUTERSandM;INC., DESIGNCAD 3.1, $299andM;DesignCAD 3.1 requires only 512K bytes of memory, making it suitable for640K-byte computers with network drivers loaded.andP;  However, it cannot use morethan 768K bytes of expanded memory, which can be a problem when using filesof about 1M byte.andM;DesignCAD imported the DXF files into its format without any problems.andO;However, it enlarged the largest file from 457K bytes to 509K bytes.andM;The other two files were smaller than VersaCAD/386's files but larger thanthe AutoCAD files.andM;DesignCAD compared favorably with AutoCAD and VersaCAD/386 in the networktests, at a considerably smaller price.andP;  It took the longest amount of timesaving the largest file on both networks.andP;  But it was about 40 percent fasterthan VersaCAD in loading the nozzle file onto the 3Com network, and it tookabout the same amount of time as VersaCAD/386 to load the Columbia file.andM;DesignCAD is available in a 3-D version for modeling and is supported by manysymbol libraries from the manufacturer.andM;American Small Business Computers Inc. of Pryor, Okla., can be reached at(918) 825-4844.andM;----------Buyers say: Good value, no file lockingandM;&quot;It's a good buy for the money,&quot; said Harvey Diez, president of D-Tech Inc.,andO;a network consulting firm in Tulsa, Okla.andM;Diez was impressed with DesignCAD's speed and said DesignCAD comparedfavorably for the money with VersaCAD's rendering program.andP;  Diez analyzedDesignCAD for possible installation at another site.andM;&quot;It runs on a network, but it's not set up to have a multiuser situation.andP;  Itdoesn't have automatic file-locking.andP;  Usually software built into a networkversion would have that,&quot; he said.andM;Diez found a problem when two users were working from the same hard disk.andP;  Ifthe temporary files created for each drawing aren't properly labeled bysubdirectory or by user, they can be overlaid onto another user's drawing, hesaid.andM;He cautioned that program files should be put on each user's disk, whiledrawing files should be stored on the server, adding that this means buyingone copy of the product for each user.andM;</TEXT></DOC>